To Kindle A Light

by J. Vasilevic

I'm pulled from the thrills and chills of my addictive crime drama by the realisation that we are slowing down. The last few hours have flown by. The train is finally approaching my stop and through the window, a beautiful New Zealand valley starts to come into focus. I place my PJ Tracy into my rucksack and stretch and yawn.

My eyes feel like the proverbial pissholes in the snow. At this point I've been travelling roughly thirty two hours pretty much non-stop. Four hours to Heathrow, twenty two or so hours to Wellington, and then another six hours on this rickety old uncomfortable train. I've now got a twenty five minute walk from the station to my uncle's old farmhouse to complete my journey. However if I'm being honest, I'm looking forward to finally getting to use my legs.

My uncle Mark recently passed. He was a batchelor with no other living relatives but my brother and I. He named me the executor of his estate, so I'm making the pilgrimage to his old farm house to sort out his belongings and generally clean the place up before we place the property on sale. A task easier said than done when the property is half way across the world.

Luckily, the weather is warm and pleasant. It's 6:32 pm local time and the sun is setting, giving the horizon a beautiful yellow-purple hue.

The train comes to a stop and huffs a sigh of relief.

CARRIAGE

I'm sat on the carriage, which is now stopped and ticking over quietly. One or two people disembark onto the small platform, whilst one or two others carry on reading or typing on a laptop or whatever they are doing to pass the time. The carriage is now practically empty.

Outside, the valley forest gleams with a warm gold. I can hear the whistling of evening birdsong.

The carriage exit onto the platform is open to my west.
> w

> w

I grab my rucksack and disembark off the train carriage onto the lonely, quaint station platform.

The train blows its funnel and horn and slowly starts to chug away into the distance.

PLATFORM

This place really is in the middle of absolutely nowhere. The station and the track are the only noticeable signs of civilisation in the entire valley. Elsewhere there is nothing but forestry.

Stood at the other end of the station is a small red shack that was obviously once a functioning ticket office, but doesn't seem to have been in service for many years, possibly many decades. Next to the shack is a billboard and a small green bench.

A footpath heading up the hill heads off from the platform to my west.
> x shack

> x shack
The smell of old dust and damp makes me squint a little and gives me the urge to sneeze. The little old shack has obviously served this station for countless years but is now nothing more than a humble relic. It's red paint is crumbling off in large patches and it looks utterly infested with woodworm. I'm surprised it's still standing.

At the front of the shack is a window pane which has been left slightly ajar.
> x window

> x window
The window at the front of the shack is rusted and cracked, but has been left open. There doesn't seem to be anything of interest inside, apart what looks like a small piece of paper leaning against the inside of the glass.
> take paper

> take paper
I reach my hand into the dusty gloom of the shack and manage to to grab it. I blow the dust off and, to my not so pleasant surprise, it happens to be a photograph of my uncle Mark.
> w

> w

PATH

I'm walking up the steep path, heading up towards the top of the valley. The forest canopy covers the path clearing in a blanket of shade, yet the yellow dusk light is still just about strong enough to illuminate the way before the darkness truly sets in.

It's odd. I usually feel threatened walking by myself in places like this. Today I feel relaxed. Almost serene.

Anyway, It's an enjoyable walk but there's nothing much here apart from trees and mud. Onwards and upwards.

The path continues up the hill to the west. The train station is back down the hill to the east.
> w

> w

After following the forest path for  another twenty minutes or so, the suddenly familiar sight of the crusty old red gate at the head of my uncle's drive comes into view.

Well, I say "drive"... It's essentially nothing more than a worn pitch of grass eroded by tyre tracks and neglect.

Helpfully, the gate is padlocked shut, so with a heave that was deeper than it should be for a woman of my age, I swing not so gracefully over the gate onto the dry mud on the other side.

GROUNDS

I'm stood in the green, dry, muddy grounds of my uncle's cottage. The place looks remarkably well kept, considering its age.

The drive runs up to the garage to the north. There is also a little path leading off to the west towards the front door of the house. The path back to the train station heads past the rusty old gate to the south.
> w

> w

COTTAGE FRONT

I'm stood under the rustic little wooden archway that serves as a porch to the cottage. It's still a deceptively large property. Its low, with only one storey plus a little attic space if I remember correctly, but it commands a large surface area.

Facing me northwards is a nauseating lime green door that's seen better days. Along the wall a few yards to my left is a dirty old metallic window. Next to me, stood up against the wall alongside the wooden archway is a chopped log. Presumably Uncle Mark still kept himself warm the old fashioned way.

The garage door is just across the path to my east. The path heading back to the gate is south.
> take chopped log

> take chopped log
Ok, I've taken the log.
> unlock lime green door

> unlock lime green door
I grab the bundle of keys out of my bag and start attempting to unlock the door. After a lengthy process of elimination, the door finally unlocks with a click.
> n

> n

FRONT CORRIDOR

I take a single step into the front corridor and immediately halt. I'm hit square in the face by an unimaginably potent smell of faeces and excrement. It's so  overpowering that I have to practically dive back out through the door in time to stop myself from vomitting where I'm standing.

I take a few steps away from the house, compose myself and turn around.

Through the front door I can only see into the front corridor, but it's all I need to see. The walls are quite literally caked in shit. It's everywhere. Floor to ceiling. So thick in places, it's remained in clumps.

Hundreds of flies are hovering around the larger masses. It's probably fair to say the amount of larvae festering and growing inside is exponentially higher.

My mind has gone blank...

What the fuck...what happened?!? was this uncle Mark?!? What happened?!?

I start crying uncontrollably. The thought of my uncle living like this...In this...

Had he lost his mind?...

Fifteen minutes pass. I've been sat on the lawn attempting to calm myself enough to try and figure out how to approach the house. Figuratively and literally.

GROUNDS

I'm stood in the green, dry, muddy grounds of my uncle's cottage. The place looks remarkably well kept, considering its age.

The drive runs up to the garage to the north. There is also a little path leading off to the west towards the front door of the house. The path back to the train station heads past the rusty old gate to the south.
> n

> n

A GARAGE FRONT

I'm stood in the middle of the field in front of the old aluminium garage door. It's crooked and buckled but it still seems to hold in place. A rusted padlock is locking the door in place at the bottom.

The front door of the cottage is over to my west. Further over to my east in the middle of the field is the old gazebo.
> use chopped log on padlock

> use chopped log on padlock
With a deep breath I thump the end of the log against the padlock. The padlock practically crumbles into two pieces and collapses onto the ground. I throw the broken remains of the log away and lift up the stiff garage door. It creaks and heaves but manages to stay open.
> n

> n

GARAGE

I'm stood inside the damp mouldy garage attached to the side of the cottage. It's a large room, extending all the way to the rear of the house.

In front of me is an old Landrover, covered in a thick layer of dust. I'm guessing it hasn't been used in a while.

Drilled haphazardly onto the walls are rows of home-made shelving, adorned with typical household and garage paraphernalia. Paint pots, power tools, mysterious old boxes and other random junk accumulated over the years.

Straight ahead northwards, the garage continues into it's gloomy rear. The outside is behind me southwards.
> switch on torch

> switch on torch
I switch it on.
> n

> n

GARAGE REAR

I'm in the rear end of the garage. The area is cluttered with even more junk than the front. There is a number of trunks and chests stacked up here and more shelves are fixed onto these walls.

A reenforced door to the west leads into the rear of the house. The front of the garage is back to the south.
> x rear shelves

> x rear shelves
Not much here. Some rolls of plastic and a couple of tarpaulins. There's also an assortment of cleaning products here.
> take cleaning products

> take cleaning products
Ok, I've taken the cleaning products.
