> s

GARAGE

I'm stood inside the damp mouldy garage attached to the side of the cottage. It's a large room, extending all the way to the rear of the house.

In front of me is an old Landrover, covered in a thick layer of dust. I'm guessing it hasn't been used in a while.

Drilled haphazardly onto the walls are rows of home-made shelving, adorned with typical household and garage paraphernalia. Paint pots, power tools, mysterious old boxes and other random junk accumulated over the years.

Straight ahead northwards, the garage continues into it's gloomy rear. The outside is behind me southwards.
